<section xml:id="section-isolating-a-linear-variable" permid="ZhA">
  <title>Isolating a Linear Variable</title>
  <objectives permid="aBo">
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul permid="toM">
      <li permid="ZvV"><xref ref="mth60-solve-for-variable" /></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction permid="GIx">
    <p permid="dav">
      In this section,
      we will learn how to solve linear equations and inequalities with more than one variable.
    </p>

    <figure permid="JhE">
      <caption>Alternative Video Lessons</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-dHg2rXIoZ69w7rxb3gAAaB" />
    </figure>
  </introduction>

  <subsection permid="FoJ">
    <title>Solving for a Variable</title>
    <p permid="gEV">
      The formula of calculating a rectangle's area is <m>A=\ell w</m>,
      where <m>\ell</m> stands for the rectangle's length,
      and <m>w</m> stands for width.
      When a rectangle's length and width are given,
      we can easily calculate its area.
    </p>

    <p permid="MMe">
      What if a rectangle's area and length are given,
      and we need to calculate its width?
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="OIv">
      <p permid="QMd">
        If a rectangle's area is given as
        <quantity>
          <mag>12</mag><unit base="meter" exp="2"/>
        </quantity>, and its length is given as
        <quantity>
          <mag>4</mag><unit base="meter"/>
        </quantity>, we could find its width this way:
        <md permid="RvX">
          <mrow>A\amp=\ell w</mrow>
          <mrow>12\amp=4w</mrow>
          <mrow>\divideunder{12}{4}\amp=\divideunder{4w}{4}</mrow>
          <mrow>3\amp=w</mrow>
          <mrow>w\amp=3</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p permid="wTm">
        If we need to do this many times,
        we would love to have an easier way,
        without solving an equation each time.
        We will solve for <m>w</m> in the formula <m>A=\ell w</m>:
        <md permid="xDg">
          <mrow>A\amp=\ell w</mrow>
          <mrow>\divideunder{A}{\ell}\amp=\divideunder{\ell w}{\ell}</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{A}{\ell}\amp=w</mrow>
          <mrow>w\amp=\frac{A}{\ell}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>

    <p permid="sTn">
      Now if we want to find the width when <m>\ell=4</m> is given,
      we can simply replace <m>\ell</m> with <m>4</m> and simplify.
    </p>

    <p permid="Zaw">
      We solved for <m>w</m> in the formula <m>A=\ell w</m> once,
      and we could use the new formula
      <m>w=\frac{A}{\ell}</m> again and again saving us a lot of time down the road. <!--This is why we need to learn how to solve for a variable in an equation. -->Let's look at a few examples.
    </p>

    <remark>
      <p permid="FhF">
        Note that in solving for <m>A</m>,
        we divided each side of the equation by <m>\ell</m>.
        The operations that we apply,
        and the order in which we do them,
        are determined by the operations in the original equation.
        In the original equation <m>A=\ell w</m>,
        we saw that <m>w</m> was <em>multiplied</em> by <m>\ell</m>,
        and so we knew that in order to
        <q>undo</q> that operation,
        we would need to <em>divide</em>
        each side by <m>\ell</m>.
        We will see this process of <q>un-doing</q>
        the operations throughout this section.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-profit-revenue-cost" permid="JYC">
      <statement>
        <p permid="Mck">
          Solve for <m>R</m> in <m>P=R-C</m>.
          (This is the relationship between profit, revenue, and cost.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="mPG">
        <p permid="FDe">
          To solve for <m>R</m>, we first want to note that <m>C</m> is
          <em>subtracted</em> from <m>R</m>.
          To <q>undo</q> this, we will need to <em>add</em>
          <m>C</m> to each side of the equation:
          <md permid="dKp">
            <mrow>P\amp=\attention{R}-C</mrow>
            <mrow>P\addright{C}\amp=\attention{R}-C\addright{C}</mrow>
            <mrow>P+C\amp=\attention{R}</mrow>
            <mrow>R\amp=P+C</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-slope-intercept" permid="qfL">
      <statement>
        <p permid="sjt">
          Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>y=mx+b</m>.
          (This is a line's equation in slope-intercept form.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="SWP">
        <p permid="lKn">
          In the equation <m>y=mx+b</m>,
          we see that <m>x</m> is multiplied by <m>m</m> and then <m>b</m> is added to that.
          Our first step will be to isolate <m>mx</m>,
          which we'll do by subtracting <m>b</m> from each side of the equation:
          <md permid="JRy">
            <mrow>y\amp=m\attention{x}+b</mrow>
            <mrow>y\subtractright{b}\amp=m\attention{x}+b\subtractright{b}</mrow>
            <mrow>y-b\amp=m\attention{x}</mrow>
          </md>
          Now that we have <m>mx</m> on its own,
          we'll note that <m>x</m> is multiplied by <m>m</m>.
          To <q>undo</q> this,
          we'll need to divide each side of the equation by <m>m</m>:
          <md permid="pYH">
            <mrow>\divideunder{y-b}{m}\amp=\divideunder{m\attention{x}}{m}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{y-b}{m}\amp=\attention{x}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=\frac{y-b}{m}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <warning permid="NhD">
      <p permid="fVb">
        It's important to note in <xref ref="example-solve-for-variable-slope-intercept">Example</xref>
        that each <em>side</em> was divided by <m>m</m>.
        We can't simply divide <m>y</m> by <m>m</m>,
        as the equation would no longer be equivalent.
      </p>
    </warning>

    <example permid="WmU">
      <statement>
        <p permid="YqC">
          Solve for <m>b</m> in <m>A=\frac{1}{2}bh</m>.
          (This is the area formula for a triangle.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="zdY">
        <p permid="RRw">
          To solve for <m>b</m>,
          we need to determine what operations need to be <q>undone.</q>
          The expression <m>\frac{1}{2}bh</m> has multiplication between
          <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>b</m> and <m>h</m>.
          As a first step,
          we will multiply each side of the equation by <m>2</m> in order to eliminate the denominator of <m>2</m>:
          <md permid="WfQ">
            <mrow>A\amp=\frac{1}{2}\attention{b}h</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}A\amp=\multiplyleft{2}\frac{1}{2}\attention{b}h</mrow>
            <mrow>2A\amp=\attention{b}h</mrow>
          </md>
          As a last step, we will <q>undo</q>
          the multiplication between <m>b</m> and <m>h</m> by dividing each side by <m>h</m>:
          <md permid="CmZ">
            <mrow>\divideunder{2A}{h}\amp=\divideunder{\attention{b}h}{h}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{2A}{h}\amp=\attention{b}</mrow>
            <mrow>b\amp=\frac{2A}{h}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-standard-form" permid="Cud">
      <statement>
        <p permid="ExL">
          Solve for <m>y</m> in <m>2x+5y=10</m>.
          (This is a linear equation in standard form.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="flh">
        <p permid="xYF">
          To solve for <m>y</m>,
          we will first have to solve for <m>5y</m> by subtracting <m>2x</m> from each side of the equation.
          After that, we'll be able to divide each side by <m>5</m> to finish solving for <m>y</m>:
          <md permid="iui">
            <mrow>2x+5\attention{y}\amp=10</mrow>
            <mrow>2x+5\attention{y}\subtractright{2x}\amp=10\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
            <mrow>5\attention{y}\amp=10-2x</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{5\attention{y}}{5}\amp=\divideunder{10-2x}{5}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{10-2x}{5}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p permid="loO">
        As we will learn in later sections,
        the result in <xref ref="example-solve-for-variable-standard-form">Example</xref>
        can also be written as <m>y=\frac{10}{5}-\frac{2x}{5}</m> which can then be written as <m>y=2-\frac{2}{5}x</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-celsius-fahrenheit" permid="iBm">
      <statement>
        <p permid="kEU">
          Solve for <m>F</m> in <m>C=\frac{5}{9}(F-32)</m>.
          (This represents the relationship between temperature in degrees Celsius and degrees Fahrenheit.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Lsq">
        <p permid="efO">
          To solve for <m>F</m>,
          we first need to see that it is contained inside a set of parentheses.
          To get the expression <m>F-32</m> on its own,
          we'll need to eliminate the
          <m>\frac{5}{9}</m> outside those parentheses.
          One way we can <q>undo</q> this multiplication is to divide each side by <m>\frac{5}{9}</m>.
          As we learned in <xref ref="section-linear-equations-and-inequalities-with-fractions">Section</xref> though,
          a better approach is to instead multiply each side by the reciprocal of <m>\frac{5}{9}</m>,
          which is <m>\highlight{\frac{9}{5}}</m>:
          <md permid="OBr">
            <mrow>C\amp=\frac{5}{9}(\attention{F}-32)</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{\frac{9}{5}}C\amp=\multiplyleft{\frac{9}{5}}\frac{5}{9}(\attention{F}-32)</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{9}{5}C\amp=\attention{F}-32</mrow>
          </md>
          Now that we have <m>F-32</m>,
          we simply need to add <m>32</m> to each side to finish solving for <m>F</m>:
          <md permid="uIA">
            <mrow>\frac{9}{5}C\addright{32}\amp=\attention{F}-32\addright{32}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{9}{5}C+32\amp=\attention{F}</mrow>
            <mrow>F\amp=\frac{9}{5}C+32</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

